2 Data Set Processing and Normalization (Results from Assignment 1)

2.1 Data Set Selection and Acquisition

The dataset that I chose is GSE120891 (Differential expression of genes in fibroblasts and epithelial cells infected with dsDNA viruses), which consists of RNA-seq data for fibroblast and epithelial cells that have either been infected by a mock virus (control condition) or infected with one of three different types of viruses (HCMV/human cytomegalovirus/human betaherpesvirus 5 with three different strains TB40, FIX, and AD169; HSV1/herpes simplex virus; and Ad5/adenovirus serotype 5) in the test conditions.

This dataset is of interest to me because it explores how cells change when exposed to viruses - either to try and fight off the invader or because of the effects of the virus within the cell as it aims to reproduce. This sort of data could hint at what sorts of molecular defenses the cell has - with potential applications in trying to boost the body’s natural immunity - as well as what sorts of pathways viruses trigger to trick the cell into accepting its DNA and taking over.

2.2 Data Set Cleaning

A total of 41763 genes were removed from the data set with a counts per million measurement too low to be reliably analyzed.

2.3 Identifier Mapping

There were 2482 genes who could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols. 100 genes could still be mapped by using old (GRCh37) symbols, while an additional 18 genes could be mapped by translating GRCh37 gene names into HGNC identifiers, which gives an end total of 2366 rows that could not be resolved to HUGO symbols. The remaining genes appear to largely be clone-based genes or Havana/Vega transcipts that are largely unannotated and do not have a HGNC identifier, and so were removed.

There were 13 rows with non-unique HUGO identifiers, though all but 13 were the result of missing HUGO identifiers (and so not particularly relevant). Further analysis of the duplicates show that they invariably correspond to overlapping areas, usually splice variants. To resolve this issue and avoid the fragmentation of coutns for the same gene, each set of counts with the same HUGO identifier was added up.

2.4 Dataset Overview Statistics

A total of 60725 transcripts were measured in the experiment. Of these, 18962 (31.2260189%) had a high enough counts per million measurement for the measurements to be reliable. Of the analyzable transcripts, 16600 (87.5435081%) had valid HUGO identifiers that could be found with 16583 (87.4538551%) corresponding to a unique HUGO identifier, giving a total final coverage of 16600 genes, 27.3363524% of the original data set.

Replicates were kept seperate throughout the process and in the final processed data. Since each experimental group only had 2 replicates, combining or averaging them together would not have made much of a difference to the overall size of the data set, and keeping both sets of data preserves more information, particularly if they diverge to a significant extent (with only 2 replicates, we cannot be sure which is the outlier - or if both are).

2.5 Data Normalization

The box plot and density plots indicate that there isn’t a particularly large amount of variation between the samples as a whole, with medians approximately equal in the boxplots and the density distributions roughly aligned as well. Nevertheless, normalization can still help.

Trimmed Mean of M-values (TMM) was chosen as the normalization method as this is the standard method for normalizing RNA-seq data where our assumption is that the genes are not differentially expressed.

As there was not very much variability between the samples in the first place, the post-normalized box plot appears quite similar to the pre-normalized box plot. However, the distribution of each group appears to be roughly in the same range, which indicates successful normalization.

Just as in the box plot, the density plot has not changed substantially either (as the original density plot was not highly variant in the first place). Nonetheless it can be observed that the distribution near the lower values of log-counts per million is slightly more clustered and regular than from before normalization; most of the variation itself is now in the actual shape of the distributions, as is desired.

The MDS plot shows roughly three larger clusters of samples, with the replicates tending to be very close to each other and cells from the same cell line tending to be relatively close to each other, which is more or less as would be expected from the experimental setup. The lack of any samples wildly far away from anything else indicates that none of them are overall significant outliers.

# Break up the sample names into their constituent parts for mapping to factors
samples <- data.frame(lapply(colnames(counts_normalized),

#samples <- data.frame(t(samples))

# Need to deal with various inconsistencies in the naming scheme
# The LNA samples have the infection agent and cell type swapped around
cell_types <- samples["cell_type", ]
columns_to_swap <- cell_types == "Mock" | cell_types == "HCMV"
samples["cell_type", columns_to_swap] <- samples["infection_agent", columns_to_swap]
samples["infection_agent", columns_to_swap] <- cell_types[columns_to_swap]

# The Ad5 and HSV samples do not have cell type labelled (they are all MRC5)
missing_cell_types <- grepl("^[0-9]", samples["cell_type", ])
samples["cell_type", missing_cell_types] <- "MRC5"

# Strip the extra characters off of the "TB40/E" strain
samples["infection_agent", ] <- gsub("TB40/E", "TB40", samples["infection_agent", ])

# Annotate HCMV strains as HCMV
samples["infection_agent", ] <- gsub("(AD169|FIX|TB40)", 
                                     "HCMV-\\1", samples["infection_agent", ])

# Samples labelled just "HCMV" are actually HCMV-TB40
samples["infection_agent", ] <- gsub("^HCMV$", "HCMV-TB40", samples["infection_agent", ])

# Rename references to HFF cells
hff_cells <- grepl("LNA", samples["cell_type", ])
samples["cell_type", hff_cells] <- "HFF"

The first step in determining differences between our two groups of choice is to choose the factors used in the model. An MDS plot of the normalized data (using the Limma package Ritchie et al. (2015)) coloured by infection type (CMV or mock) is shown in Figure 3.1, which demonstrates quite clearly the differing profile between the two treatments. # Limma linear model - code adapted from Ruth Isserlin (2020)
model_design <- model.matrix(~ samples$infection_agent)
expressionMatrix <- as.matrix(normalized_samples_of_interest[, -(1:3)])
rownames(expressionMatrix) <- normalized_samples_of_interest$ensembl_gene_id
minimalSet <- Biobase::ExpressionSet(assayData = expressionMatrix)

# Fit data to model and compute differential expression
fit <- limma::lmFit(minimalSet, model_design)
fit2 <- limma::eBayes(fit, trend=TRUE)
topfit <- limma::topTable(fit2, 
                   coef=ncol(model_design),
                   adjust.method = "BH",
                   number = nrow(expressionMatrix))
# Merge hgnc names and ensembl identifiers to topfit table
output_hits <- merge(normalized_samples_of_interest[, 1:3],
                     topfit,by.y=0, by.x=1, all.y=TRUE)
# Sort table by pvalue
output_hits <- output_hits[order(output_hits$P.Value), ]

# Get the number of genes that pass the threshold (p = 0.05)
(num_significant_genes_simple <- length(which(output_hits$P.Value < 0.05)))
## [1] 10127

An initial differential gene expression analysis on the two factors was done using code adapted from Isserlin (2020a), using the linear model of the Limma package Ritchie et al. (2015). Using this, it was determined that 10127 out of 9 genes were significantly differentially expressed, given a threshold of \(p < 0.05\). 0.05 was chosen for the threshold as it is the standard of choice, particularly for more exploratory data/experiments such as this one where we are more interested in screening for genes that might be worthy of further, more rigourous analysis under these conditions. 

# Multiple hypothesis testing correction
significant_genes_logical <- p.adjust(output_hits$P.Value, method = "bonferroni") < 0.05
(num_significant_genes_corrected <- sum(significant_genes_logical))
## [1] 1793

The p-values were corrected using the Bonferroni multiple hypothesis correction method, which was chosen due to the large number of samples which passed the threshold (making it feasible to narrow down the search more stringently to get rid of false positives) and the relatively small number of samples and hypotheses (which means that the correction is not as overly conservative as it might be in other samples). 1793 passed the correction.

Figure 3.5: Heatmap of Statistically Significantly Differentially Expressed Genes

A heatmap of all genes passing the Bonferroni multiple hypothesis correction test is displayed in Figure 3.5, made using the ComplexHeatmap package (Gu, Eils, and Schlesner (2016)) and adapted from code by Isserlin (2020a). There is a very strong clustering of the two factors, with all the HCMV-infected samples and all the mock-infected samples segregated into two highly distinct categories. This was also reflected in the genes, which were also cleanly seperated into two categories (either strong to very strongly expressed across the HCMV samples and weak to very weak in the mock or vice versa - there were virtually no cases of a gene whose change in expression in one particular was a different sign to any of the others in that factor), neatly seperating the heatmap into 4 strongly-coloured quadrants. While quite stark, it is not completely unexpected given the wide seperation of the conditions in the MDS plot (Figure ?? or the fact that this geneset was chosen using the generally highly conservative Bonferroni-corrected, which would ensure that only highly differentiated genes pass the filter and are plotted in the heatmap. The large number of statistically significant genes, even under the Bonferroni correction, may also be a reflection of a generally large change in expression overall between the two factors, so choosing the most differentiated ones is likely to reflect this as well.

Thresholded over-expression analysis was performed using the g:Profiler g:GOSt tool (Kolberg and Raudvere (2019)), using the hypergeometric/Fisher’s exact test and the standard threshold of 0.05, for the three annotation databases GO, Reactome, and WikiPathways. Fisher’s exact test was chosen as it is the preferred test for comparing the classification of discrete, categorical data (like our genes) between two different sets of categories (statistically signficiant expression differences or not, presence in a genelist or not). Bonferroni multiple hypothesis testing correction was used for GO due to the large size of the returned query, making it feasible to use the more powerful and conservative correction and still get a large, workable set of annotations, while the g:SCS algorithm was used for the Reactome and WikiPathways queries in order to get a larger list of plausible candidates. Of the annotation databases, GO was chosen as the best source of annotations for gene functions in general, while Reactome and WikiPathways were chosen as two separate but complementary sources to get a clearer idea of what pathways are possibly involved or affected. g:Profiler uses the most recent updates for these data resources - as of the time of analysis, the 2019-07-01 update for GO, the 2019-10-2 for Reactome, and the 20190910 update for WikiPathways.

Using the standard threshold of 0.05, we get 291 terms from the GO query, 17 terms from the GO query, and 6 terms from the WikiPathways query. There is a good mix of terms, but other than the very general large GO terms they all cluster into about three categories: structure and extracellular interactions, signalling pathways, and biosynthetic pathways (Tables 3.3, 3.4, and 3.5).

Do the over-representation results support conclusions or mechanism discussed in the original paper?
